    "questions": [
        {
            "id": "10edf80fc78e46919b232",
            "questionText": "A muon is created in the upper atmosphere at an altitude of 10 km ($!$10 \\times 10^3 \\text{ m}$!$) above the Earth's surface. The muon has a proper half-life of 2.2 microseconds ($!$2.2 \\times 10^{-6} \\text{ s}$!$) and is traveling towards the Earth at a speed of 0.99$!$c$!$, where $!$c$!$ is the speed of light. Accounting for time dilation, determine the average distance the muon will travel as observed from Earth before it decays.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "83895611a55f49398f711",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the proper half-life of the muon (its lifetime in its own rest frame). Look at the problem statement and extract that value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2.2e-6"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "bb0b6d22-6ec2-4604-812f-a427b7b70055"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "24476fa7d43948a38ae6a",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, to account for time dilation due to the muon\u2019s high speed, you need to recall the formula that relates the proper time interval $!$\\Delta t'$!$ to the dilated time $!$\\Delta t$!$. Which of the following formulas is used in time dilation?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0b935911-e793-4b1e-99f1-b6338367d9d5",
                        "a0d65d2b-9a39-4a41-bda5-09be98a1c66a"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta t = \\gamma \\Delta t'$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta t = \\Delta t'/\\gamma$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta t = \\gamma^2 \\Delta t'$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "0b52f615aafb4e60a5340",
                    "stepText": "Next, to determine the time dilation effect, you need the gamma factor. Identify the correct formula for the gamma factor from the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a0d65d2b-9a39-4a41-bda5-09be98a1c66a"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\gamma = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-\\frac{v^2}{c^2}}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\gamma = \\sqrt{1-\\frac{v^2}{c^2}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\gamma = 1 - \\frac{v}{c}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "53d69efec87242bebe37c",
                    "stepText": "Now, using the gamma factor formula and the given speed $!$v=0.99c$!$, calculate the gamma factor. Provide your answer as a numerical value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "7.09"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a0d65d2b-9a39-4a41-bda5-09be98a1c66a"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "bcc7d298eed1452092a81",
                    "stepText": "With the gamma factor determined, apply the time dilation formula to compute the dilated lifetime as observed from Earth. Multiply the proper half-life by the gamma factor. What is the dilated lifetime?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "15.6e-6"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0b935911-e793-4b1e-99f1-b6338367d9d5",
                        "a0d65d2b-9a39-4a41-bda5-09be98a1c66a"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "743dfb5dd140426a85b74",
                    "stepText": "Finally, compute the distance the muon travels in the Earth's frame by multiplying its speed by the dilated lifetime. Assume $!$c=3 \\times 10^8\\text{ m/s}$!$ and that $!$v=0.99c$!$. What is the distance traveled as observed from Earth?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "4.63e3"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "af99d217-2569-4adb-aea1-e7a319f682ac"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "832178bca54643dd9fef0",
            "questionText": "An astronaut is traveling in a spaceship moving at a constant speed of $!$0.8c$!$ relative to Earth. The spaceship has a rest length of $!$100$!$ meters ($!$L_0 = 100$!$ m). The astronaut fires a laser pulse from the back of the spaceship towards the front (in the direction of motion). What is the time taken for the laser pulse to reach the front of the spaceship according to the Earth observer's frame of reference?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "e8be408cf19b4de0afb37",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the contracted length of the spaceship as seen by an Earth observer. To do that, we need to use the length contraction concept. Which of the following formulas correctly represents the length contraction relation in special relativity?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "8f95aa1b-0eb7-42ba-bd59-8b8b8322f61a",
                        "a2cc780f-e223-46ae-8ac0-d8b76d0c5385"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$L = L_0 \\sqrt{1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$L = L_0 \\left(1 - \\frac{v}{c}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$L = L_0 \\left(1 + \\frac{v}{c}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "e93b223688bb4bef9d29d",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you have determined how to get the contracted length, let\u2019s set up an equation for the situation. In the Earth frame, the front of the spaceship is initially at the contracted length $!$L$!$ from the back. As time passes, the front moves forward with speed $!$v$!$ while the laser pulse moves with speed $!$c$!$. Which equation correctly relates the distance travelled by the light pulse to the initial gap and the distance the front moves?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "af99d217-2569-4adb-aea1-e7a319f682ac"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$c t = L + v t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$c t = L - v t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$c t = L \\cdot v t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "acac3567321f4fd79263a",
                    "stepText": "Now, using the equation you identified, solve for the time $!$t$!$ that it takes for the laser pulse to reach the front of the spaceship. Remember to substitute the contracted length and the speeds (with $!$c = 3\\times10^8\\,m/s$!$ and $!$v = 0.8c$!$) as needed. What is the numerical value for $!$t$!$ in seconds?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1e-6"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "af99d217-2569-4adb-aea1-e7a319f682ac"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
